ation":"I discovered a HTTP-Response-Splitting issue on v.shopify.com\n\nSteps to reproduce:\nCall the following URL in any browser and catch the response ( e.g. with burp )\nhttps://v.shopify.com/last_shop?shop=krankopwnz.myshopify.com%0d%0aContent-Length:%200%0d%0a%0d%0aHTTP/1.1%20200%20OK%0d%0aContent-Type:%20text/html%0d%0aContent-Length:%2019%0d%0a%0d%0a\u003chtml\u003edeface\u003c/html\u003e\n\nWhen you look at screenshot 1 in attachments, you can see that the response contains 2 headers.\n\nAccording to OWASP, this could be used for \" Cross-User Defacement, Cache Poisoning, Cross-site Scripting (XSS) and Page Hijacking.\" ( https://www.owasp.org/index.php/HTTP_Response_Splitting )\n\nYou could convince victims via social engineering to click the provided link, which can contain a cloned login-page of shopify for example. If he sits behind a proxy, which caches the responses the following users will see your evil login-page when calling that address.\n\nA fix would be to disallow line-breaks and any non printable characters in the \"shop\"-parameter","vulnerability_information_html":"\u003cp\u003eI discovered a HTTP-Response-Splitting issue on v.shopify.com\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSteps to reproduce:\u003cbr\u003e\nCall the following URL in any browser and catch the response ( e.g. with burp )\u003cbr\u003e\n\u003ca title=\"https://v.shopify.com/last_shop?shop=krankopwnz.myshopify.com%0d%0aContent-Length:%200%0d%0a%0d%0aHTTP/1.1%20200%20OK%0d%0aContent-Type:%20text/html%0d%0aContent-Length:%2019%0d%0a%0d%0a\" href=\"/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Fv.shopify.com%2Flast_shop%3Fshop%3Dkrankopwnz.myshopify.com%250d%250aContent-Length%3A%25200%250d%250a%250d%250aHTTP%2F1.1%2520200%2520OK%250d%250aContent-Type%3A%2520text%2Fhtml%250d%250aContent-Length%3A%252019%250d%250a%250d%250a\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\"\u003e\u003cspan\u003ehttps://v.shopify.com/last_shop?shop=krankopwnz.myshopify.com%0d%0aContent-Length:%200%0d%0a%0d%0aHTTP/1.1%20200%20OK%0d%0aContent-Type:%20text/html%0d%0aContent-Length:%2019%0d%0a%0d%0a\u003c/span\u003e\u003ci class=\"icon-external-link\"\u003e\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u0026lt;html\u0026gt;deface\u0026lt;/html\u0026gt;\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWhen you look at screenshot 1 in attachments, you can see that the response contains 2 headers.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAccording to OWASP, this could be used for \u0026quot; Cross-User Defacement, Cache Poisoning, Cross-site Scripting (XSS) and Page Hijacking.\u0026quot; ( \u003ca title=\"https://www.owasp.org/index.php/HTTP_Response_Splitting\" href=\"/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.owasp.org%2Findex.php%2FHTTP_Response_Splitting\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\"\u003e\u003cspan\u003ehttps://www.owasp.org/index.php/HTTP_Response_Splitting\u003c/span\u003e\u003ci class=\"icon-external-link\"\u003e\u003c/i\u003e\u003c/a\u003e )\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eYou could convince victims via social engineering to click the provided link, which can contain a cloned login-page of shopify for example. If he sits behind a proxy, which caches the responses the following users will see your evil login-page when calling that address.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eA fix would be to disallow line-breaks and any non printable characters in the \u0026quot;shop\u0026quot;-parameter\u003c/p\u003e\n","bounty_amount":"500.0","formatted_bounty":"$500","original_report_id":null,"original_report_url":null,"attachments":[{"id":66445,"file_name":"screenshot1-responseSplitting.jpg","expiring_url":"https://hackerone-us-west-2-production-attachments.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/000/066/445/434d292159b1226ee4b84d373a501c87927fb8c7/screenshot1-responseSplitting.jpg?response-content-disposition=attachment%3B%20filename%3D%22screenshot1-responseSplitting.jpg%22%3B%20filename%2A%3DUTF-8%27%27screenshot1-responseSplitting.jpg\u0026response-content-type=image%2Fjpeg\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=ASI